   <titles>
      <title>Linear Transformations Between Subvector Spaces of <math>
            <latex>\RNr[k]</latex>
         </math>
      </title>
      <plain.title>Linear Maps Between Subspaces</plain.title>
   </titles>
   <intro>
      <block>
         <block.body>
            <para>
               <para.body>In this section we extend what we learned about linear maps <math>
                     <latex>\RNr[n]\to \RNr[m]</latex>
                  </math> to subvector spaces of <math>
                     <latex>\RNr[k]</latex>
                  </math>.</para.body>
            </para>
         </block.body>
      </block>
   </intro>
   <body>
      <block>
         <block.body>
            <def type="Definition" id="Def_LinearMapBetweenSubspaces">
               <caption>Linear transformation</caption>
               <associate type="Comment">
                  <unit.ref unitId="Expla_LinearTrafoGeneral"/>
                  <info>
                     <para>
                        <para.body>Comment and Explanation</para.body>
                     </para>
                  </info>
               </associate>
               <def.body>
                  <para>
                     <para.body>Let <math>
                           <latex>V</latex>
                        </math> and <math>
                           <latex>W</latex>
                        </math> be subvector spaces of <math>
                           <latex>\RNr[k]</latex>
                        </math>. A linear transformation from <math>
                           <latex>V</latex>
                        </math> to <math>
                           <latex>W</latex>
                        </math> is a function <math>
                           <latex>L\from V\to W</latex>
                        </math> such that</para.body>
                  </para>
                  <ul>
                     <li>
                        <para>
                           <para.body>
                              <emphasis>Additivity</emphasis>   <math>
                                 <latex>L(\Vect{x}+\Vect{y}) = L(\Vect{x}) + L(\Vect{y})</latex>
                              </math> for all <math>
                                 <latex>\Vect{x}</latex>
                              </math>, <math>
                                 <latex>\Vect{y}</latex>
                              </math> in <math>
                                 <latex>V</latex>
                              </math>.</para.body>
                        </para>
                     </li>
                     <li>
                        <para>
                           <para.body>
                              <emphasis>Commutes with scalar multiplication</emphasis>   <math>
                                 <latex>L(t\Vect{x}) = t L(\Vect{x})</latex>
                              </math> for all <math>
                                 <latex>\Vect{x}</latex>
                              </math> in <math>
                                 <latex>V</latex>
                              </math> and all <math>
                                 <latex>t</latex>
                              </math> in <math>
                                 <latex>\RNr</latex>
                              </math>.</para.body>
                        </para>
                     </li>
                  </ul>
               </def.body>
            </def>
            <para>
               <para.body>All operations and constructions we performed on linear maps <math>
                     <latex>\RNr[n]\to \RNr[m]</latex>
                  </math> are, in essence, available for linear maps <math>
                     <latex>V\to W</latex>
                  </math>. To explain how this goes, we begin with
			<subordinate>
                     <hot>new linear maps from old</hot>
                     <crossref>
                        <unit.ref unitId="Sec_LinearTransformationsNewFromOld"/>
                        <info>
                           <para>
                              <para.body>Earlier we constructed</para.body>
                           </para>
                           <ul>
                              <li>
                                 <para>
                                    <para.body>the sum of two linear transformations</para.body>
                                 </para>
                              </li>
                              <li>
                                 <para>
                                    <para.body>the scalar product of a linear transformation by a number</para.body>
                                 </para>
                              </li>
                              <li>
                                 <para>
                                    <para.body>the composition of two linear transformations</para.body>
                                 </para>
                              </li>
                           </ul>
                           <para>
                              <para.body>Look up how this was done.</para.body>
                           </para>
                        </info>
                     </crossref>
                  </subordinate>.</para.body>
            </para>
            <xi:include xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude" href="NewLinearFromOld_Thm.xml"/>
            <para>
               <para.body>We know that linear maps <math>
                     <latex>\RNr[n]\to \RNr[m]</latex>
                  </math> correspond to matrices of size <math>
                     <latex>(m,n)</latex>
                  </math>. The key to this relationship between linear maps and matrices is the following proposition.</para.body>
            </para>
            <xi:include xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude" href="LinearMapByBasis_Thm.xml"/>
            <para>
               <para.body>... and here it is: the relationship between linear maps and matrices.</para.body>
            </para>
            <xi:include xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude" href="LinearMapMatrix_Thm.xml"/>
            <para>
               <para.body>Addition of linear transformations corresponds to addition of representing matrices, and composition of linear transformation corresponds to multiplication of representing matrices in the following precise sense.</para.body>
            </para>
            <xi:include xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude" href="MatrixSumLinears_Thm.xml"/>
            <xi:include xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude"
                        href="MatrixScalarProductLinearMap_Thm.xml"/>
            <xi:include xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude"
                        href="MatrixCompositionLinearMaps_Thm.xml"/>
            <xi:include xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude"
                        href="ChangeCoordinatesLinearMap_Thm.xml"/>
         </block.body>
      </block>
